In the U.S., bluefish are landed primarily in recreational fisheries, but important commercial fisheries also exist in temperate and subtropical waters.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=  http://www.nefsc.noaa.gov/sos/spsyn/op/bluefish/|title= Bluefish_ Status of Fishery Resources off the Northeastern US}}&lt;/ref&gt;
Bluefish population abundance is typically cyclical, with abundance varying widely over a span of 10 years or more.&lt;ref name=Ulanski&gt;Ulanski, Stan (2011) [https://books.google.com/books?id=fNqu1nrQbyoC&amp;pg=PA103&amp;lpg=PA103&amp;dq=Bluefish+cannibalistic&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=0jdgrk__3o&amp;sig=diGbexjGlTutRc6eSXR-r6RUDoU&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=gsJoUKGaIJCPiAfR1oHIDw&amp;ved=0CDMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&amp;q=Bluefish%20cannibalistic&amp;f=false ''Fishing North Carolina's Outer Banks''] University of North Carolina Press. {{ISBN|9780807872079}}.&lt;/ref&gt;

==Management==
Bluefish is a popular sport and food fish, and has been widely overfished.&lt;ref&gt;http://icesjms.oxfordjournals.org/content/64/3/531.full&lt;/ref&gt; Fisheries management has generally stabilized its population. In the middle Atlantic region of the U.S., bluefish were [[Overfishing|heavily overfished]] in the late 1990s, but active management rebuilt the [[fish stock|stock]] by 2007.&lt;ref name=FishWatch&gt;[http://www.fishwatch.gov/seafood_profiles/species/bluefish/species_pages/bluefish.htm Bluefish] ''FishWatch'', NOAA. Retrieved 5 October 2012.&lt;/ref&gt;  Elsewhere, public awareness efforts, such as bluefish festivals, combined with catch limits, may be having positive effects in reducing the stress on the regional stocks.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url= http://www.treehugger.com/green-food/istanbul-celebrates-new-hope-for-a-favorite-fish-with-first-annual-la14fer-festival.html|title= Istanbul Celebrates New Hope for a Favorite Fish With First-Annual 'Lüfer Festival'}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==As food==
Bluefish may be baked or poached,&lt;ref name=&quot;admed&quot;&gt;Alan Davidson, ''Mediterranean Seafood'', 3rd edition, 2002, {{isbn|1580084516}}, p. 100&lt;/ref&gt; or smoked.&lt;ref name=&quot;mkt&quot;/&gt; The smaller ones (&quot;snapper blues&quot;) are generally fried, as they are not very oily.&lt;ref name=&quot;adatl&quot;&gt;Alan Davidson, ''North Atlantic Seafood'', 1980, {{isbn|0670515248}}, p. 92-93&lt;/ref&gt;

Because of its fattiness, bluefish goes rancid rapidly, so it is generally not found far from its fisheries,&lt;ref name=&quot;mkt&quot;&gt;{{cite book|title=Fish Market: A Cookbook for Selecting and Preparing Seafood|page=87}}&lt;/ref&gt; but where it is available, it is often inexpensive.&lt;ref name=&quot;sifton&quot;&gt;[https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1014240-smoked-bluefish-pate Sam Sifton, &quot;Smoked Bluefish Pâté&quot;, ''New York Times'']&lt;/ref&gt; It must be refrigerated and consumed soon after purchase; some recipes call for keeping it in vinegar and wine before cooking, in ''vina d'alhos''&lt;ref name=&quot;adatl&quot;/&gt; or ''[[en escabeche]]''.&lt;ref&gt;[https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/5915-bluefish-escabeche Florence Fabricant, &quot;Bluefish Escabeche&quot;, ''New York Times'' Cooking]&lt;/ref&gt; By the same token, it is high in [[omega-3 fatty acids]], but also in [[mercury in fish|mercury]] and [[Polychlorinated biphenyl|PCBs]],&lt;ref name=&quot;mkt&quot;/&gt; containing the high level of about 0.4 ppm of mercury on average,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |url=|doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2010.12.034 |title=Mercury and selenium levels in 19 species of saltwater fish from New Jersey as a function of species, size, and season |journal=Science of the Total Environment|year=2011 |last1=Burger |first1=Joanna |last2=Gochfeld |first2=Michael |volume=409 |issue=8 |pages=1418–1429 |pmid=21292311 |pmc=4300121 |bibcode=2011ScTEn.409.1418B }}&lt;/ref&gt; comparable to [[albacore tuna]] or [[Spanish mackerel]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=https://www.fda.gov/food/foodborneillnesscontaminants/metals/ucm115644.htm |title=Mercury Levels in Commercial Fish and Shellfish (1990-2012) |website=FDA |access-date=13 August 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt; For that reason, the U.S. [[FDA]] recommends that young children and women of childbearing age consume no more than one serving per week (a serving size is about 4 ounces uncooked for an adult, 2 ounces for children ages 4–7 years, 3 ounces for children ages 8–10 years, and 4 ounces for children 11 years and older).&lt;ref&gt;U.S. Food &amp; Drug Administration, &quot;Eating Fish: What Pregnant Women and Parents Should Know&quot; [https://www.fda.gov/Food/ResourcesForYou/Consumers/ucm393070.htm]&lt;/ref&gt;

